WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.040
Earlier in training, you learned the listen,
acknowledge, ask, redirect framework, and

2
00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:07.380
the most common objections.

3
00:00:07.740 --> 00:00:10.740
That covers probably 80% of what you'll
hear.

4
00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:17.180
This section covers the other 20%, which is
the complex, unusual, and

5
00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:21.760
sometimes uncomfortable stuff that makes
most people on the phone freeze up.

6
00:00:22.750 --> 00:00:27.640
These situations are harder because they
carry more emotional weight, more legal

7
00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:30.380
complexity, or more moving pieces.

8
00:00:30.835 --> 00:00:32.264
But the framework is the same.

9
00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:35.520
You just need more depth in how you apply
it.

10
00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:41.620
When a seller says, I owe more than it's
worth, that's an underwater property.

11
00:00:42.148 --> 00:00:45.291
The mortgage balance is higher than what the
house would sell for.

12
00:00:45.537 --> 00:00:50.397
This is more common than you'd think, especially
in certain markets and with people who

13
00:00:50.397 --> 00:00:52.969
bought at the wrong time or took out second
mortgages.

14
00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:57.620
Your job here is to understand the full
financial picture.

15
00:00:58.020 --> 00:01:01.120
Ask if they're current on their payments or
falling behind.

16
00:01:01.640 --> 00:01:02.940
Ask roughly what they owe.

17
00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:05.640
Sometimes a short sale structure can work.

18
00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:08.160
Sometimes it's genuinely not a fit.

19
00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:11.480
Either way, don't make them feel bad about
it.

20
00:01:11.700 --> 00:01:15.780
Being underwater is stressful and a lot of
people are embarrassed to talk about it.

21
00:01:16.560 --> 00:01:20.320
When they say, I have tenants, can I still
sell?

22
00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:25.620
The answer is yes. We buy properties with
tenants all the time.

23
00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:30.140
The questions you need answered are whether
the tenants are on a lease, whether they're

24
00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:33.800
paying rent, and whether they'd be willing
to stay or need to move.

25
00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:39.920
If there's a squatter situation, someone
living in the property without a lease or

26
00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:42.260
permission, that's more complicated.

27
00:01:42.820 --> 00:01:45.220
Acknowledge how frustrating that is.

28
00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:50.580
Say something like, that sounds incredibly
frustrating and we've dealt with situations

29
00:01:50.580 --> 00:01:54.160
like that before. Let me get the details and
see what we can do.

30
00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:58.100
Don't promise a solution, just gather
information.

31
00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:03.860
Leaseback requests come up when someone needs
the cash from selling but isn't ready to

32
00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:08.520
move yet. Maybe they're waiting for a new
place to be ready, or they need a few months

33
00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:12.480
to get situated. They'll ask, can I stay in
the house after selling?

34
00:02:12.878 --> 00:02:15.402
And the answer is that it's something we can
discuss.

35
00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:20.300
A leaseback means they'd stay as a tenant
for a defined period after closing.

36
00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:22.960
You don't need to negotiate the terms
yourself.

37
00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:26.980
Just say, that's something our acquisition
team handles on the specifics.

38
00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:30.040
But yes, we've done arrangements like that
before.

39
00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:32.480
Let me get the details of what you'd need.

40
00:02:33.860 --> 00:02:36.920
Privacy concerns are more common than you
might expect.

41
00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:40.060
I don't want my neighbors to know I'm
selling.

42
00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:42.600
There's usually something behind that.

43
00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:45.280
Financial trouble they don't want people to
see.

44
00:02:45.620 --> 00:02:50.360
A divorce, family drama, whatever it is, the
answer is simple.

45
00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:56.520
When you sell to us, there's no listing on
the MLS, no sign in the yard, no open houses,

46
00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:58.460
no strangers walking through.

47
00:02:58.920 --> 00:03:00.320
It's a private transaction.

48
00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:05.460
Contract fears. What if I change my mind
after signing?

49
00:03:06.120 --> 00:03:10.020
People are scared of commitment, especially
with something as big as their house.

50
00:03:10.420 --> 00:03:15.240
Tell them the contracts have an inspection
period built in, that everything gets walked

51
00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:16.520
through before they sign,

52
00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:21.120
that nothing happens until they're comfortable,
and that they'll have time to have an

53
00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:24.020
attorney or anyone they trust review
everything.

54
00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:27.240
You're reducing the perceived risk of saying
yes.

55
00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:30.500
So that's the situation side.

56
00:03:30.840 --> 00:03:33.300
The property, the money, the paperwork.

57
00:03:33.560 --> 00:03:36.880
But some of the hardest objections aren't
about the property at all.

58
00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:39.320
They're about trust. Is this a scam?

59
00:03:39.429 --> 00:03:41.477
Are you just going to flip it for a profit?

60
00:03:41.477 --> 00:03:43.877
My attorney said, don't sign anything.

61
00:03:44.338 --> 00:03:45.481
My family doesn't agree.

62
00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:47.060
That's the next lesson.

63
00:03:47.317 --> 00:03:48.222
I'll see you there.
